00:05:55.930 --> 00:05:56.540
identity providers.

00:05:56.540 --> 00:05:59.760
So social login is a big
example, enterprise API

00:05:59.760 --> 00:06:01.190
integration is another one.

00:06:01.190 --> 00:06:03.930
For those websites, sure, it's
a lot of work to support

00:06:03.930 --> 00:06:05.180
identity providers.

00:06:05.180 --> 00:06:07.640
But they got a lot of bang for
the buck from it, not just

00:06:07.640 --> 00:06:08.220
getting rid of passwords.

00:06:08.220 --> 00:06:10.220
A lot of other API
[? probably. ?]

00:06:10.220 --> 00:06:11.990
But what about all the
rest of the websites?

00:06:11.990 --> 00:06:14.580
They may be just trying to get
out of the password business.

00:06:14.580 --> 00:06:17.630
They're not ready to do all that
fancy API integration.

00:06:17.630 --> 00:06:19.500
So for them, a lot of work.

00:06:19.500 --> 00:06:20.900
Not as much value.

00:06:20.900 --> 00:06:23.450
And in fact, what we find is
they don't even recognize

00:06:23.450 --> 00:06:25.840
upfront necessarily
how hard it is.

00:06:25.840 --> 00:06:28.270
There are hard problems that
lead to a lot of users calling

00:06:28.270 --> 00:06:29.000
help desks.

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:30.980
And that drives websites
crazy because it

00:06:30.980 --> 00:06:32.280
drives up their costs.

00:06:32.280 --> 00:06:35.590
There are also really hard
questions and edge cases to do

00:06:35.590 --> 00:06:37.410
with what we refer to
as account linking.

00:06:37.410 --> 00:06:39.200
So you may have seen
this yourself.

00:06:39.200 --> 00:06:41.390
You go to a website
that added one of

00:06:41.390 --> 00:06:42.590
these buttons for login.

00:06:42.590 --> 00:06:45.020
You click it, and the website
says, oh, you have an existing

00:06:45.020 --> 00:06:45.510
account here.

00:06:45.510 --> 00:06:47.920
Why don't you go through this
wizard to bind your existing

00:06:47.920 --> 00:06:50.400
account to this new account
and connect them together?

00:06:50.400 --> 00:06:52.890
Building those flows and
handling all the edge cases is

00:06:52.890 --> 00:06:54.390
a lot of work.

00:06:54.390 --> 00:06:56.830
Now fortunately, there are
vendors who are starting to

00:06:56.830 --> 00:06:59.310
provide software and services
to make this easier.

00:06:59.310 --> 00:07:01.910
So in fact, this same website,
accountchooser.net, it has a

00:07:01.910 --> 00:07:03.110
link for website owners.

00:07:03.110 --> 00:07:06.400
And down at the bottom, a link
to more information about

00:07:06.400 --> 00:07:08.770
identity providers and
vendors who can help.

00:07:08.770 --> 00:07:10.820
And we're getting better
and better at this.

00:07:10.820 --> 00:07:12.820
But not to the point
that it's easy.

00:07:12.820 --> 00:07:15.780
We're also doing further
optimizations to the protocols

00:07:15.780 --> 00:07:18.320
like OpenID Connect and other
tricks to address some of

00:07:18.320 --> 00:07:20.570
these user experience problems
and make it simple.

00:07:20.570 --> 00:07:23.160
But to be honest, there is
still some ways to go.

00:07:23.160 --> 00:07:25.250
TIM BRAY: And bear in mind, the
cost of not doing it, as

00:07:25.250 --> 00:07:27.330
you pointed out, is
still pretty high.

00:07:27.330 --> 00:07:27.570
ERIC SACHS: Yes.

00:07:27.570 --> 00:07:28.830
TIM BRAY: So where
do you start?

00:07:28.830 --> 00:07:30.490
What's the first step?

00:07:30.490 --> 00:07:31.660
ERIC SACHS: So there
at least there is

00:07:31.660 --> 00:07:32.220
some pretty good news.

00:07:32.220 --> 00:07:33.660
This website we referred
to, it's called

00:07:33.660 --> 00:07:34.100
accountchooser.net.

00:07:34.100 --> 00:07:36.640
And you might be wondering,
OK, well what the heck is

00:07:36.640 --> 00:07:38.240
Account Chooser itself?

00:07:38.240 --> 00:07:41.390
What we've found is that to
address these problems a

00:07:41.390 --> 00:07:44.610
website is having, I mentioned
one set of problems is users

00:07:44.610 --> 00:07:46.120
calling help desks
with confusion.

00:07:46.120 --> 00:07:48.200
A lot of that is around
the user experience.

00:07:48.200 --> 00:07:50.830
And so the industry, actually
a bunch of what we like to

00:07:50.830 --> 00:07:53.420
call backstabbing competitors,
Google and others, have

00:07:53.420 --> 00:07:56.850
actually developed a user
experience we're happy with

00:07:56.850 --> 00:08:00.190
that actually helps a website
who's purely password based,

00:08:00.190 --> 00:08:02.730
not doing anything with
identity providers.

00:08:02.730 --> 00:08:05.070
And once actually a website is
[INAUDIBLE] that, they tend to

00:08:05.070 --> 00:08:08.100
really like that, then it's
actually pretty easy for them

00:08:08.100 --> 00:08:10.560
to do staged deployment of
identify providers in a more

00:08:10.560 --> 00:08:11.610
controlled manner.

00:08:11.610 --> 00:08:14.720
But before we talk about that,
Tim, why don't you just run

00:08:14.720 --> 00:08:15.260
through a demo?

00:08:15.260 --> 00:08:15.500
TIM BRAY: Sure.

00:08:15.500 --> 00:08:17.020
Yeah, this is one of my
favorite little demos.

00:08:17.020 --> 00:08:19.970
I've got this little website
called favcolor.net

00:08:19.970 --> 00:08:20.780
that does one thing.

00:08:20.780 --> 00:08:23.310
It remembers your
favorite color.

00:08:23.310 --> 00:08:25.360
And when I go there,
you see this thing.

00:08:25.360 --> 00:08:28.660
This is not favcolor branded
except in the right side of

00:08:28.660 --> 00:08:29.180
the screen there.

00:08:29.180 --> 00:08:31.975
This is the cross-account
Account Chooser.

00:08:31.975 --> 00:08:34.429
It remembers all the accounts
I've used to log in to one

00:08:34.429 --> 00:08:35.390
thing or another.

00:08:35.390 --> 00:08:37.559
So you can see I have
my personal address,

00:08:37.559 --> 00:08:38.070
textuality.com.

00:08:38.070 --> 00:08:41.179
And I can log into that
using Facebook.

00:08:41.179 --> 00:08:43.270
And it went to the
Facebook IDP.

00:08:43.270 --> 00:08:44.910
And it says, oh, I know
your favorite color.

00:08:44.910 --> 00:08:46.665
It's this nice royal purple.

00:08:46.665 --> 00:08:50.230
We'll just turn it into a lurid
pink and save that.

00:08:50.230 --> 00:08:52.980
So that's now my favorite
color, a lurid pink.

00:08:52.980 --> 00:08:56.370
So I can switch over and log in
