have access through my Gmail

00:09:22.070 --> 00:09:23.250
account here.

00:09:23.250 --> 00:09:26.360
Now, if I click on that one, it
says, oops, I haven't been

00:09:26.360 --> 00:09:27.000
there before.

00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:29.830
So Google pops up and
says, is it OK to do

00:09:29.830 --> 00:09:31.100
this with this account?

00:09:31.100 --> 00:09:33.130
And I say, yeah, sure,
that's OK.

00:09:33.130 --> 00:09:34.900
And it goes back to
Account Chooser.

00:09:34.900 --> 00:09:37.400
Now, if you look carefully at
the fine print here, it says,

00:09:37.400 --> 00:09:38.690
we don't know your
favorite color.

00:09:38.690 --> 00:09:40.210
So we're picking
one at random.

00:09:40.210 --> 00:09:42.160
So what I was showing
you there was not

00:09:42.160 --> 00:09:43.936
one click sign in.

00:09:43.936 --> 00:09:47.040
It was one click sign up, which
is starting to become

00:09:47.040 --> 00:09:50.040
possible with the combination
of identity providers and

00:09:50.040 --> 00:09:52.590
front end technology like
Account Choosers.

00:09:52.590 --> 00:09:53.470
Now, we're not there yet.

00:09:53.470 --> 00:09:54.750
Account Chooser is available.

00:09:54.750 --> 00:09:56.370
We're still working on
technologies to get it better

00:09:56.370 --> 00:09:59.160
bootstrapped for a better
end user experience.

00:09:59.160 --> 00:10:02.370
But it's really starting to
be a potential reality.

00:10:02.370 --> 00:10:03.570
So we do make process.

00:10:03.570 --> 00:10:04.520
ERIC SACHS: Yes.

00:10:04.520 --> 00:10:07.210
And so one of the key things
that Tim mentioned is while

00:10:07.210 --> 00:10:09.800
this works great, once your
website is in this future

00:10:09.800 --> 00:10:12.340
world with identity providers,
think about a website who's

00:10:12.340 --> 00:10:13.870
still doing everything
with passwords.

00:10:13.870 --> 00:10:16.150
A user comes to a site
like this one.

00:10:16.150 --> 00:10:18.650
They click an email address that
the operating system, the

00:10:18.650 --> 00:10:20.760
browser, whatever it is, and
there are cross platform ways

00:10:20.760 --> 00:10:22.350
to do this, knows
are frequently

00:10:22.350 --> 00:10:23.640
used on this device.

00:10:23.640 --> 00:10:25.420
The user clicks their
email address.

00:10:25.420 --> 00:10:26.930
That email address comes
to this website.

00:10:26.930 --> 00:10:29.230
And now your website gets
to start being smart.

00:10:29.230 --> 00:10:31.560
The first thing it can do is
say, oh, I've seen that email

00:10:31.560 --> 00:10:32.640
address before.

00:10:32.640 --> 00:10:34.360
So let me ask the user
for a password.

00:10:34.360 --> 00:10:36.480
Or it can say, well, I haven't
seen it before.

00:10:36.480 --> 00:10:38.130
So let me show a sign-up form.

00:10:38.130 --> 00:10:40.245
Let me pre-fill the email
address and get the user to

00:10:40.245 --> 00:10:40.890
fill it out.

00:10:40.890 --> 00:10:42.783
So all of a sudden, you've at
least avoided the need for the

00:10:42.783 --> 00:10:45.810
user to remember sign in, to
sign up, and you've avoided

00:10:45.810 --> 00:10:47.950
the need for them to retype
the email address, which

00:10:47.950 --> 00:10:50.770
especially on mobile devices,
is a huge win.

00:10:50.770 --> 00:10:53.770
It ends up this is a very
small amount of work for

00:10:53.770 --> 00:10:55.540
websites to get deployed.

00:10:55.540 --> 00:10:57.250
And I think Tim can
speak to that.

00:10:57.250 --> 00:11:00.710
However, what really becomes
powerful is now you get to do

00:11:00.710 --> 00:11:04.520
what we call percentage
experiments, controlled

00:11:04.520 --> 00:11:06.180
experiments with identity
providers.

00:11:06.180 --> 00:11:07.700
Where what you could
do on your website,

00:11:07.700 --> 00:11:08.610
say, you know what?

00:11:08.610 --> 00:11:11.800
Let me pick all the users who
are, say, Gmail email

00:11:11.800 --> 00:11:15.370
addresses who start with the
letter A. And any time one

00:11:15.370 --> 00:11:17.280
comes to our website and clicks
an email address that

00:11:17.280 --> 00:11:20.280
meets that criteria, then I'm
going to do as Tim described.

00:11:20.280 --> 00:11:23.620
I'm going to bounce them over
to Google, use Google as an

00:11:23.620 --> 00:11:26.000
identity provider, and
bring them back.

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:28.310
And I was mentioning before that
the industry as a whole

00:11:28.310 --> 00:11:30.980
is working to the user
experience, the technology,

00:11:30.980 --> 00:11:34.020
Google supports the latest
versions of OpenID Connect.

00:11:34.020 --> 00:11:36.710
And in fact, in that, there's
this optimization we have

00:11:36.710 --> 00:11:39.340
where the website can say, hm,
I already know the email

00:11:39.340 --> 00:11:40.760
address the user is using.

00:11:40.760 --> 00:11:42.650
So let me start a flow
with Google.

00:11:42.650 --> 00:11:44.565
And tell them, hey, I already
got the user's email address.

00:11:44.565 --> 00:11:46.450
I just want to know whether that
email address is logged

00:11:46.450 --> 00:11:48.710
in here. yes or no,
[? nothing like ?] that.

00:11:48.710 --> 00:11:50.100
And that's what Google
responds back.

00:11:50.100 --> 00:11:53.460
We just respond back to
the website yes or no.

00:11:53.460 --> 00:11:55.760
And if the website sees yes,
then it says, oh, OK.

00:11:55.760 --> 00:11:57.430
Well, the user clicked the email
address they wanted.

00:11:57.430 --> 00:11:59.160
I know they're logged into
that email address.

00:11:59.160 --> 00:12:00.550
Let me just log them in.

00:12:00.550 --> 00:12:03.440
There's no user experience
change for users here.

00:12:03.440 --> 00:12:05.480
They just go to the site, click
the account they want.

00:12:05.480 --> 00:12:07.900
And instead of being asked for a
password and then logged in,

00:12:07.900 --> 00:12:09.450
they're just logged in.

00:12:09.450 --> 00:12:12.560
So you can do this with, say,
a small percentage of users.

00:12:12.560 --> 00:12:15.060
And start to see, OK,
does it impact other

00:12:15.060 --> 00:12:16.940
parts of your website?

00:12:16.940 --> 00:12:19.800
And then you can try to, say,
delete passwords from some of

00:12:19.800 --> 00:12:20.380
those users.

00:12:20.380 --> 00:12:21.820
And you'll probably find
things in your

00:12:21.820 --> 00:12:22.585
website that do break.

00:12:22.585 --> 00:12:25.080
Your mobile apps might be hard
coded for passwords.

00:12:25.080 --> 00:12:27.690
Your account management page
might be hard coded for that.

00:12:27.690 --> 00:12:30.060
And you can go and start
tracking those things down,

00:12:30.060 --> 00:12:31.760
fix them, get it changed.

00:12:31.760 --> 00:12:34.410
And then, over time, add support
for more fancy things

00:12:34.410 --> 00:12:38.080
like identity providers who
are not email providers or

00:12:38.080 --> 00:12:39.740
social network providers
or enterprise

00:12:39.740 --> 00:12:41.240
providers, et cetera.

00:12:41.240 --> 00:12:44.910
And so we believe that most
websites who want to at least

00:12:44.910 --> 00:12:47.400
show that they're starting to
get out of the password

00:12:47.400 --> 00:12:49.580
business, this is a first
step you can take.

00:12:49.580 --> 00:12:52.040
Because as Tim mentioned, for
all you know, next week is the

00:12:52.040 --> 00:12:54.475
week that your security guys are
going to tell you you've

00:12:54.475 --> 00:12:56.500
been hacked, and you have to
announce to the world that

00:12:56.500 --> 00:12:57.980
everybody has to reset
the passwords.

00:12:57.980 --> 00:12:59.230
That is huge branch damage.

00:12:59.230 --> 00:13:00.810
Somebody's getting fired.

00:13:00.810 --> 00:13:03.590
If you can at least show that
you've taken this as a first

00:13:03.590 --> 00:13:05.860
step and you're headed in the
right direction, that's a good

00:13:05.860 --> 00:13:08.770
level of insurance that you can
buy yourself without doing

00:13:08.770 --> 00:13:11.380
as much work and sets you up to
do some of the experiments

00:13:11.380 --> 00:13:14.730
we provide as the industry and
the vendors in this space try

00:13:14.730 --> 00:13:17.070
to work to make it easier and
easier for websites to make

00:13:17.070 --> 00:13:17.540
this happen.

00:13:17.540 --> 00:13:19.230
TIM BRAY: So we kind of know
what the future looks like.

00:13:19.230 --> 00:13:22.510
And we are actually providing
something of an on ramp.

00:13:22.510 --> 00:13:24.210
Start working here, and that's
where you'll get there.

